@Whoa Nellie

Well done!
Billy Preston would be proud!

@Eric Hougland

I’m sure it’s edited by humans and the varying level of difficulty might be by design, but the game itself is exactly up a language model’s alley. 

@Whoa Nellie 

Ha, speaking of a comforting blanket that compliments. I’ve appealed to ChatGPT via I don’t know how many settings to please, please stop being so smarmy and obsequious. I don’t need to be validated by a research assistant, AI or human. Yet ChatGPT persists, which leads me to believe that most end users find the endless flattery (“Oh, Sam, now this is the kind of incisive question I live for!”) well, flattering. So yes, I do worry what the coming years will bring. How quickly will we be lulled into self-satisfied submission?

Maybe you and I will hold out a bit longer? My husband has been dishing out nerdy humor I adore for half of my life now, but if you’ll ask him how much complacency on my part it’s earned him, well…

@Eric Hougland

As my particular ChatGPT is unaccountably fond of saying (he didn’t get it from me, that’s for sure): Chef’s kiss! [smile]

(Yes, I anthropomorphize my AI tool. @Whoa Nellie will probably never let me live it down…)

@Sam Lyons
I don’t disagree with your calling a natick on that crossing as I believe all naticks are personal, revealing what you know or don’t know in certain areas.
I am interested, however, when folks connect their unfamiliarity with Harry Potter to be related to their not having children. I have never had children, yet I have read the books, enjoyed the movies and even listened to the audiobooks during my morning walks because I so much enjoyed the writing, hue plot and the character development. On the other hand I tried to read LOTR and couldn’t get past the first hundred pages, and never watched a single episode of GOT. I have no explanation for that, it’s just interesting to me.

@Sam Lyons

I have unsuccessfully tried to post a comment on this thread more than five times! I keep getting the "error posting, please copy/paste your comment and try again" message. 

So this is a test! Fingers crossed!

@Gary
I’m told (and maybe by now I’ve seen it in the archives but don’t remember) that the eponymous Natick was clued as the town that hosts a pretty long stretch of the Boston Marathon. And, I might add, it’s a stretch you hit while you’re still conscious of things other than your body screaming for you to stop, for Freyya’s sake STOP. So, personally speaking, I don’t see how Naticky Natick could have been for the solvers that day; I mean, at least 30K of us know it well. [grin]

@Eric H. 
My nieces are reading Harry Potter on their own, but I want to be able to talk to them about it, you know? Which is why I’ll finally tackle the series, though it’s really—and I mean, really—not my thing. Even as a kid I wasn’t a fan of fantasy as much as all my friends. It didn’t get better with age—as big a fan as u am of Tolkien’s scholarship, I was never able to get through LOTR. 

Which brings me to your other point. I didn’t think I was being dismissive of animated children’s movies, and of course there is value in them for both kids and adults. My point was merely that, by and large, their audiences are kids and adults with kids, and having two proper names from children’s and YA literature and/or movies cross each other runs counter to how most NYT puzzle handle their trivia clues. Especially when the two names in question don’t draw from the pool of first names you’d see in English or most other languages.

@Vislander
You give me hope that now that I’ll be tackling Harry Potter so that I can be *the* cool aunt, maybe it won’t be the slog I’m expecting. I’m with you on LOTR and I don’t get the appeal of the Game of Thrones at all. But then I do realize I lack the fantasy genre gene…

@Jin
Where did I conflate pop culture with Harry Potter books? I didn’t even have them in the same paragraph. 

@G
I’ve noticed that our emu overlords have been finicky lately. 

@The X-Phile
I would draw a distinction between being familiar with something and knowing the names of other-than-titular characters and very specific plot references. The bottom line is that when it’s down to that last letter in the puzzle, and you’re unlikely to know the two names in the cross unless you’ve  actually read the book/seen the movie, *and* it’s not a name that otherwise exists in the pantheon of English-language names, *and* both clues are drawn from the segment of our culture that a large portion of the population participates in, then it’s more than a personal Natick. Or what @Bill in Detroit said up-thread, only more eloquently. 

Again, and this is meant for the thread in general: I don’t believe I was dismissive of Harry Porter books or animated films. I’m not dismissive of (almost) any books, ever, even ones with pictures. A lot of us, however, don’t have kids. Some by choice; others, like me for instance, for heartbreaking reasons. Either way, it’s a big chunk of those who do the NYT puzzle.

